:"Thiel-sur-Acolin, Allier, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Thil","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Otto, Hans, Erwin, Egon, Franz, Reinhard, Wolfgang, Angelika, Arno, Bernhard.","North German, Dutch, and Flemish: from a shortened form of the personal name <i>Thietilo</i>, an early medieval pet form of   Dietrich   (German), <i>Diederik</i> (Dutch), or from some other compound name with the same first element.","Germanized form of Sorbian, Polish, and Czech   Tyl  , a name which is (at least in part) of the same German origin as 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Thielges","meanings":["German: from a Rhenish pet form of   Thiel   1."]},{"name":"Tiell","meanings":["Altered form of German <b>Tiel</b>, a variant of   Thiel  ."]},{"name":"Tilleman","meanings":["Dutch and Flemish: patronymic from the personal name <i>Tiele</i> (see   Thiel   1).","Americanized form of German <b>Tillemann</b>, a cognate of 1 above, derived from the personal name <i>Tillo</i>."]},{"name":"Thiele","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Hans, Horst, Kurt, Reinhold, Wilhelm, Albrecht, Eberhard, Edelgard, Erna, Erwin.","North German and Dutch: variant of   Thiel   1.","Germanized form of Sorbian, Polish, and Czech   Tyl   and of its Sorbian and Polish variant <b>Tyla</b>, names which are (at least in part) of the same German origin as 1 above."]},{"name":"Tilkens","meanings":["Flemish: patronymic from a pet form of the personal name <i>Til</i>, <i>Tijl</i>, of ancient Germanic origin (see   Thiel   1)."]},{"name":"Thielmann","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Klaus, Nikolaus.","North German: patronymic or elaborated form of   Thiel  ."]},{"name":"Thielke","meanings":["North German: from a pet form of the personal name   Thiel   1.","Germanized form of Sorbian <b>Tylk</b>, <b>Tylka</b> or <b>Tylko</b>: from a pet form of the personal name   Tyl  , which is at least in part of the same German origin as 1 above."]},{"name":"Dietrich","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Otto, Gerhard, Dieter, Hans, Helmut, Juergen, Wolfgang, Fritz, Hans-Peter, Heinz, Jurgen.","German: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Theodoric</i> (see   Terry  ), composed of the elements <i>theud</i> ‘people, race’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power(ful), rich’. This surname is also found in some other European countries, notably in France (Alsace and Lorraine) and Poland. Compare   Dedrick  ,   Deitrich  ,   Detrick  , and   Tetrick  ."]},{"name":"Teel","meanings":["Probably an Americanized form of German   Thiel  .","English: variant of   Teale  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain and Ireland."]},{"name":"Thielen","meanings":["North German and Dutch: patronymic from   Thiel  ."]}]},{"name":"Guillaume","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>William</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"William","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Guillaume de Thil was born in 1275, in Thiel-sur-Acolin, Allier, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, France, his father, Pons Poincet de Thil, was 31 and his mother, Agnès de Traînel, was 25. He had at least 1 son with Isabeau de Grandpré. He died in 1317, in Marigny, Manche, Lower Normandy, France, at the age of 42."},"et":{"1275–1317":"1275–1317","1275–1325":"1275–1325","1290–1355":"1290–1355","1245–Male":"1245–Surnud","1250–Female":"1250–Surnud","1325":"1325","1245":"1245","1355":"1355","1275":"1275","1250":"1250","1290":"1290","1317":"1317","Marigny, Manche, Basse-Normandie, France":"Marigny, Manche, Basse-Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Vic-sous-Thil, Côte-d'Or, Bourgogne-Franche-Comté, France":"Vic-sous-Thil, Côte-d'Or, Bourgogne-Franche-Comté, Prantsusmaa","Thiel-sur-Acolin, Allier, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, France":"Thiel-sur-Acolin, Allier, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1275–1317":"1275–1317","1275–1325":"1275–1325","1290–1355":"1290–1355","1245–Male":"1245–Kuollut","1250–Female":"1250–Kuollut","1325":"1325","1245":"1245","1355":"1355","1275":"1275","1250":"1250","1290":"1290","1317":"1317","Marigny, Manche, Basse-Normandie, France":"Marigny, Manche, Basse-Normandie, Ranska","Vic-sous-Thil, Côte-d'Or, Bourgogne-Franche-Comté, France":"Vic-sous-Thil, Côte-d'Or, Bourgogne-Franche-Comté, Ranska","Thiel-sur-Acolin, Allier, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, France":"Thiel-sur-Acolin, Allier, Auvergne-Rhône-Alpes, Ranska"},"fr":{"1275–1317":"1275–1317","1275–1325":"1275–1325","1290–1355":"1290–1355","1245–Male":"1245–Décédé","1250–Female":"1250–Décédée","1325":"1325","1245